# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abc-news-australia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The news division also draws upon the resources of CBS News, and among non-Paramount Skydance sources, ITN (which produces 5 News UK, which is owned by Paramount), APTN and Reuters for select international coverage.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Network 10's news service was introduced on 2 August 1964 with the launch of ATV-10 in Melbourne, followed on 5 April 1965 by TEN-10 in Sydney.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The network was the first to introduce dual-anchored hour-long news bulletins in the form of *Eyewitness News* from 1973 onwards.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The 1980s were the network's most successful period as a news provider with its local Sydney, Melbourne and Brisbane bulletins often rating highest for their 6 pm timeslots.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] A major change to the service occurred on 20 January 1992 when all five of its local bulletins were moved to the 5 pm time slot.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In 1994, all local weekend bulletins were axed across the network and replaced by a 30-minute network bulletin from Sydney – *Ten Weekend News*, initially presented by John Gatfield and later by Tracey Spicer, Natarsha Belling and Bill Woods.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In September 2010, the network announced a major expansion of its news service.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] From 24 January 2011, It expanded its evening news output by introducing a national current affairs program at 6 pm, *6PM with George Negus* (later *6.30 with George Negus*), and an additional local bulletin at 6:30 pm on weeknights, under the *Ten Evening News* brand.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In addition, the network announced the re-introduction of local weekend bulletins at 6 pm and the axing of its 5 pm national bulletin.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Two months after the relaunch, the national weekend bulletins were re-introduced owing to poor ratings, although the 6 pm local bulletins continued to air.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Later that month, the network dropped its 6:30 pm local bulletins on weeknights, extended *Ten News at Five* to 90 minutes and moved George Negus' program to 6:30 pm each weeknight.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The changes were introduced on Monday 4 April 2011.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Further changes in September 2011 saw the axing of the network's late night bulletin and the state-based 6 pm weekend bulletins.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The 5 pm national bulletin on Saturdays and Sundays was extended to 90 minutes a month later.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Later that month, the network axed *6.30 with George Negus* and replaced it with an hour-long version of *The 7PM Project* (renamed *The Project*).
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In November 2011, the last half-hour of Network 10's 5 pm state bulletins were rebranded as *Ten News at Six*.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Two months later, the main 5 pm bulletin was shortened back to 60 minutes from Sunday 22 January 2012 with *The Project* moved to 6 pm.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The network's *Ten Early News* bulletin was axed in February 2012 following the launch of Network 10's *Breakfast* program.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] More changes during the year saw the return of a networked *Ten Late News* in a new format launched on 4 June 2012, and the axing of *Breakfast* on 30 November 2012, due to low ratings and cost-cutting measures at the network.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] On 15 September 2013, Network 10 reintroduced the *Ten Eyewitness News* branding for all of its news output, including the flagship 5 pm state bulletins.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Two months later, a new breakfast program, *Wake Up*, was launched.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] On 21 May 2014, Network 10 announced it would axe *Wake Up* and all national news bulletins on weekdays as part of a wider cost-cutting program with the loss of around 150 jobs, caused by poor ratings and advertising revenue.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The network also closed its two international bureaux in Los Angeles and London.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] As of 2018, the state-based 5 pm news continues to air, alongside national bulletins at weekends.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In February 2014, Network 10 announced that Hugh Riminton would join Sandra Sully as a co-anchor of the bulletin.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In November 2014, Candice Wyatt joined Stephen Quartermain as a co-anchor and finally in August 2015 Lachlan Kennedy joined Georgina Lewis as a co-anchor in Brisbane.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] On 16 May 2016, *Ten Eyewitness News* updated their set and graphics.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In January 2017, the three east coast metro bulletins (Sydney, Melbourne and Brisbane) returned to solo anchors with Hugh Riminton, Candice Wyatt and Lachlan Kennedy returning to reporting duties in February.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] On 1 November 2018, alongside a major network relaunch, the *Ten Eyewitness News* branding was replaced with *10 News First*.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] On 2 December 2019, the 5 pm edition of *10 News First* was extended to 90 minutes.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] On 11 August 2020, 10 announced it would transfer studio presentation of the Brisbane and Perth bulletins to Sydney with the Adelaide bulletin moved to Melbourne.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Reporters, camera crews and editorial staff were retained in Adelaide, Brisbane and Perth.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] An afternoon bulletin, titled *10 News First: Afternoons*, was also introduced in 2024, premiering on 29 January 2024.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] On 16 June 2025, Network 10 announced it would be rebranding its news division to *10 News*, alongside the announcement of the new public affairs program named *10 News+* which premiered on 30 June 2025.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The network's first late news bulletin, *Ten Evening News: Crisis in the Gulf*, was hosted by veteran newsreader Eric Walters and was part of the network's coverage of the First Gulf War in January 1991.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The bulletin also aired on weekends, hosted by Tracey Spicer, until the Saturday and Sunday editions were axed in 2004 and 2005 respectively.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In 2006, the bulletin was merged with the late weeknight edition of *Sports Tonight* on Monday through Thursday nights.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Due to declining ratings and increased competition, the bulletin was axed with the final week of episodes hosted by Sandra Sully (news) and Brad McEwan (*Sports Tonight*) on Monday through Thursday, and Tim Webster on Friday 30 September 2011.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Sully became co-host of Sydney's evening bulletin alongside Bill Woods.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The bulletin was revived on 4 June 2012 in a new magazine-style format, hosted by Hamish Macdonald.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In September 2013, the bulletin was rebranded as *Ten Eyewitness News: Late* and Danielle Isdale replaced Macdonald after he resigned later that same month.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Hugh Riminton later replaced Isdale as host and the bulletin returned to a standard news bulletin format.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The bulletin was again axed in May 2014 alongside the early and morning news bulletins.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In 2026, the bulletin was expanded to one hour and brought forward to start at 9:30 pm.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Since 25 May 2026, sport has been presented under the *Sports Tonight* banner, as was the case between 2006–11.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] This segment is presented by either Max Burford or Adrian Franklin on a rotating basis.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The weekend edition of *10 News* airs on Saturday and Sunday evenings at 5 pm and is presented from the network's Sydney studios by Georgie Tunny with sport presenter Scott Mackinnon and weather presenter Amanda Jason.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The national bulletin was introduced in 1994 to replace state-based bulletins (excluding Adelaide and Perth, who had state-based weekend bulletins until early 1996) but axed in January 2011 ahead of the reintroduction of local editions at 6 pm.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The national edition was reinstated two months later in the wake of poor ratings.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The 6 pm local bulletins continued to air until October 2011 when the 5 pm national news was extended to 90 minutes.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Until July 2014, a separate edition for Perth and Western Australia was also broadcast from the Pyrmont studios in Sydney.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Localised Sydney-produced weekend editions were restored for Perth and Western Australia by late 2018.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Then weeknight presenter Narelda Jacobs presented the Perth edition until she was reappointed to present the weeknight bulletins for Perth in September 2020; Bath would present both the national and Perth editions of the weekend news ever since.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In April 2026, the separate Perth bulletin presented on weekends moved production to Subiaco, and is presented by Jacobs.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In December 2018, it was announced that Natarsha Belling would move to *Studio 10* in 2019 to present news updates throughout the show.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In October 2025, Network 10 announced it would not renew Chris Bath's contract as part of a broader cost-cutting initiative.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] She would remain with network until December.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The bulletin has previously been presented by Chris Bath, Natarsha Belling, Hermione Kitson, Mike Munro, Matt Doran, Bill Woods, Steve Liebmann, Tracey Spicer and John Gatfield.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Fill-in presenters include Hugh Riminton, Amanda Hart, Taylor Ryan, Ashleigh Raper and Tallulah Thompson (news), and Chloe-Amanda Bailey (sport).
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Short, localised updates air late afternoons and early evenings by each capital city's main newsreader Monday to Friday, with national updates originating from Sydney over the weekend.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The Sydney edition is simulcast on 10 Northern NSW in Northern New South Wales and in Griffith via 10 Griffith, and across Southern New South Wales and the Australian Capital Territory via 10 Southern NSW and ACT.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Between 1995 and 2005, the bulletin was presented by Ron Wilson and Jessica Rowe, until Rowe moved to co-host *Today* on the Nine Network.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] She was replaced by former US correspondent Deborah Knight in 2006.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Wilson moved to the national *Early News* bulletin, after presenting his final 5 pm Sydney bulletin as main anchor on Friday 16 January 2009.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In October 2011, Sandra Sully replaced Deborah Knight following the axing of *Ten Late News*.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Knight left the network to join the Nine Network as a *Nine News* presenter and *Weekend Today* as a news presenter.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Bill Woods left the network on 30 November 2012 after his contract was not renewed as part of cost-cutting measures.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Ron Wilson was also set to leave on the same day, however he stayed until 28 December that year as he presented his final bulletin for Ten News after being employed there for 34 years.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] He then moved back to radio in April 2013 as a newsreader and radio announcer for smoothfm.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In February 2014, Hugh Riminton joined Sandra Sully as a co-anchor, but returned to reporting three years later when the bulletin returned to a solo-anchor format.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Fill-in presenters include Hugh Riminton, Ursula Heger and Georgie Tunny (news) and Amanda Hart (weather).
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The network's Melbourne news operation was originally based at the Nunawading studios until a move to the Como Centre in 1992.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Mal Walden joined ATV-10 in April 1987, shortly after his abrupt sacking by HSV-7 – he took over the weekday 5 pm bulletin in 1996 alongside Jennifer Hansen who was replaced by Helen Kapalos in 2006.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Kapalos was sacked in November 2012 amid cost-cutting measures at the network.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Walden anchored the bulletin solo until his retirement in December 2013.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] George Donikian was the main male fill-in during the 2000s, including presenting the Saturday 6 pm bulletin during the 2002–11 period that Network 10 had the AFL broadcasting rights.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Sport presenter Stephen Quartermain then assumed that role, though he had filled-in as news presenter during various times in the past, when Donikian was unavailable.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Mignon Stewart (née Henne) was the main female fill-in for Jennifer Hansen and Helen Kapalos during the 2000s (including for an extended stint in early 2006 before Kapalos started).
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] There was no female fill-in for much of 2008 and 2009.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Hermione Kitson became the female fill-in during 2010 and moved to Sydney in 2012.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] During the 2000s, occasionally due to availability and network commitments, Walden or Kapalos would present solo (particularly after major events such as the AFL Grand Final).
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Traffic Reporter Vanessa O'Hanlon left after six years (2003–2008) in 2008 for *ABC News Breakfast*.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Emma Notarfrancesco left after four and a half years (2010–2015), to work for Formula 1's Australian media team on Friday 20 February 2015.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Jimmy Wirtanen then returned to the role.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In November 2014, Candice Wyatt joined Stephen Quartermain as co-anchor of the bulletin, but returned to reporting just over two years later when the bulletin returned to a solo-anchor format.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In May 2018, Network 10 announced that Jennifer Keyte would leave the Seven Network to present the bulletin replacing Stephen Quartermain, who was redeployed to his former role of presenting sport on the bulletin.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Past presenters of Network 10's Melbourne news included David Johnston, who presented the flagship evening bulletin for 16 years (alongside the likes of Jana Wendt and Jo Pearson) until his departure for HSV-7 in 1996.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The Melbourne bulletin is simulcast across most of regional Victoria via 10 Regional Victoria, to the city of Mildura via 10 Mildura, most of metropolitan and regional Tasmania via 10 TDT, the south areas of Remote and Eastern Australia via 10 Central and to the city of Darwin via 10 Darwin.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In September 2020, studio production for the Melbourne bulletin was merged with the Adelaide bulletin with opt-outs for local news, sport and weather alongside shared content; the bulletins were separated and Melbourne returned to a solo bulletin on 3 February 2023.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Fill in presenters include Jayde Cotic and Stephen Quartermain (News), Adrian Franklin and Caty Price (Sport), Steph Baumgartel and Sophie Jacobson (Weather).
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The Brisbane edition is simulcast across regional Queensland via 10 Regional Queensland, the Gold Coast via 10 Northern NSW and Gold Coast and the north areas of Remote and Central Australia via 10 Central.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Reporters are also based at a remote newsroom on the Gold Coast.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In August 2015, Lachlan Kennedy joined Georgina Lewis as co-anchor of the bulletin, but returned to reporting merely eighteen months later when the bulletin returned to a solo-anchor format.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Former long-serving presenter Marie-Louise Theile left *Ten News* on 14 December 2007 to spend more time with her family.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Other previous presenters include Geoff Mullins, Tracey Spicer, Brad McEwan and Bill McDonald, who left in November 2012 when his contract was not renewed due to cost-cutting measures.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In September 2020, studio production for the Brisbane bulletin was transferred to Sydney with a single bulletin containing opt-outs of local news, sport and weather for Sydney and Brisbane alongside shared content.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Georgina Lewis, presenter of 13 years, and sports presenter Jonathan Williams were among those that were made redundant in the restructure with the final Brisbane-based bulletin broadcast on 11 September 2020.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] On 15 August 2024, it was announced that a separate bulletin, presented from Ten's Mt Coot-tha studios, would be restored from 2 September 2024, with former reporter Sharyn Ghidella returning to the network after more than thirty years.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Fill in presenters include Pippa Sheehan, Georgina Hill (News), Josh McLean (Sport) and Paris Martin (weather).
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The Adelaide bulletin is simulcast to Port Lincoln, the Upper Spencer Gulf of South Australia and the city of Broken Hill in New South Wales via 10 Spencer Gulf and Broken Hill, and to the Riverland and the South East areas of South Australia via 10 South Australia.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In 2000, studio production for the 5 pm Adelaide bulletin was moved to the network's Melbourne studios in South Yarra.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The bulletin was presented from Melbourne for the next decade while sport and weather segments were still presented locally from the station's studios in North Adelaide and subsequently, from 2007, in newly-built studios in Hutt Street.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Initially, then-presenters George Donikian and Nikki Dwyer relocated from Adelaide to present the new Melbourne based bulletin.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] After 8 years co-anchoring with Donikian, Dwyer eventually resigned as presenter in late 2000 after she decided to move back to Adelaide, to begin starting a family.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Dwyer was subsequently replaced as presenter by Kelly Nestor who resigned in 2006 and was succeeded by Rebecca Morse.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] On 21 January 2011, George Donikian presented his final Melbourne-based bulletin for *Ten News Adelaide*.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Studio presentation subsequently returned to ADS-10's Adelaide studios on 24 January 2011, to coincide with the launch of the short-lived 6:30 pm local bulletin.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Rebecca Morse relocated with the bulletin to Adelaide while Donikian remained in Melbourne, co-presenting the Melbourne edition of *Ten News at Five* with Helen Kapalos for two months before being reduced to Fridays only, as well as presenting the localised weekend edition.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Jane Reilly retired as weather presenter in April 2013 after 37 years and was succeeded by Kate Freebairn.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] A year later, Mark Aiston resigned as sport presenter.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In September 2020, studio production for the Adelaide bulletin was transferred back to Melbourne with a single bulletin containing opt-outs of local news, sport and weather for Adelaide and Melbourne alongside shared content.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Rebecca Morse, presenter of 14 years, and sports presenter Will Goodings were among those that were made redundant in the restructure with the final Adelaide-based bulletin broadcast on 11 September 2020.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In February 2022, the Adelaide newsroom was relocated to newly-built offices on Greenhill Road in Eastwood.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The Adelaide and Melbourne bulletins were separated on 3 February 2023; studio production of the Adelaide bulletin was moved to the network's Sydney studios, where Kate Freebairn is now based, to present a new solo bulletin for Adelaide.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Tiffany Warne temporarily shifts from Weather to News, due to presenter Kate Freebairn is on maternity leave until 2026.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Fill in presenters include Alan Murrel (News).
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The Perth bulletin is simulcast to most of regional Western Australia via 10 Western Australia.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Production of the Perth bulletin was initially moved to Pyrmont in 2000, citing high costs of converting the network's Dianella studios.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Then-presenters Greg Pearce and Christina Morrissy relocated to Sydney to present the bulletin, whilst sport and weather segments were still presented locally from the station's studios in Dianella.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Morrissy later resigned from these duties after suffering deep vein thrombosis on a flight and was replaced by Celina Edmonds.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Pearce also later resigned to return to Perth, while Edmonds resigned to spend more time with her family.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] She then moved to Sky News Australia as a presenter and reporter.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Following their departures, Tim Webster and Charmaine Dragun became the main presenters of *Ten News Perth* from 2005.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] On 18 January 2008, it was announced that studio production of *Ten News* would return to Perth.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The network denied that the move was related to the death of Charmaine Dragun as the decision to switch production had been made well beforehand.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Narelda Jacobs began presenting in the Sydney studios in May 2008 before *Ten News Perth* presentation returned to the Dianella studios on Monday 23 June 2008.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In December 2016, Network 10 moved into new offices in Subiaco, relocating from Dianella.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In December 2019, it was announced that former *Today Tonight* presenter Monika Kos would replace Jacobs as anchor from 13 January 2020 with Jacobs to move to Sydney to co-host *Studio 10*.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In September 2020, studio production for the Perth bulletin was transferred back to Sydney with Narelda Jacobs returning as anchor.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The bulletin continued to air live with sports news presented from the Perth newsroom.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] On 13 March 2023, presentation of the Perth bulletin once again returned to the Subiaco studio as a trial, with Natalie Forrest as anchor.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In December 2023, it was announced that the bulletin would remain in Perth.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Fill in presenters include Jess Brown (News).
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In 10's regional viewing areas, additional local news updates air at various times during the day and evening Monday to Friday.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Updates are produced and recorded in both Sydney (Southern NSW & ACT) and Melbourne (Regional Victoria, Regional Queensland) since January 2026, with separate updates for the local areas within each state.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Current presenters are Stacey Eldridge (Southern NSW & ACT), Sarah Bennallack (Regional Victoria), and Mae James (Regional Queensland).
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] These updates were previously produced in Hobart by former regional affiliate Southern Cross Austereo while transitioning from regional affiliate ownership to network ownership.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Following 10's acquisition of NRN Northern NSW & Gold Coast in May 2025, local updates currently continue to be produced and recorded in Wollongong by *WIN News* under *10 News* branding since June 2025.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The current presenters for the local updates are Keeley Hurry and Madison Arnold, with Georgia Elsley filling-in.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Updates in Tasmania are produced independently by Seven Tasmania, who co-own 10’s local affiliate TDT alongside WIN Tasmania.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Ashleigh Raper, Georgie Tunny, Carrie-Anne Greenbank and Johnpaul Gonzo are fill-in presenters on the bulletin.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In October 2025, Network 10 announced that *10 News+* will be cut from one hour to 30 minutes from 2026.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Over the decades, Network 10 has experimented with a wide range of current affairs formats.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The network's early morning news program began as *Ten Early News* in January 2006, airing for one hour at 6 am weekday mornings and featuring a number of segments unique to its timeslot, such as morning newspaper headlines from the country's major papers.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The last edition aired on Wednesday 22 February 2012 in preparation of the earlier-than-scheduled launch of Network 10's *Breakfast* program.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The bulletin was revived on 4 November 2013 as *Ten Eyewitness News: Early*, airing from 5:30 am to 6:30 am on weekdays, immediately preceding the network's new breakfast program *Wake Up*.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The bulletin was originally presented by Bill Woods until he became a presenter for the Sydney edition of *Ten News at Five*, switching roles with Ron Wilson in January 2009.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] For the revival, Hermione Kitson anchored alongside sports presenter Scott Mackinnon and weather presenter Amanda Jason.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The final edition of the early news aired on Friday 23 May 2014, when the bulletin was axed alongside *Wake Up* and the morning and late news bulletins.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Ten originally aired a late morning news program from 1980 until cost-cutting measures led to its axing ten years later.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] It was revived in 1994 and presented by David Johnston from the Melbourne newsroom.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] From 1994–2000 and August – December 2005, *Ten Morning News* would air after the successful *Good Morning Australia with Bert Newton*.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In 1996, Jason Cameron took over as presenter for the next four years until production was moved to 10's Pyrmont news centre in Sydney, where the bulletin was hosted by Tracey Spicer and Natarsha Belling.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In 2004, the bulletin briefly moved to midday (then called *Ten News at Noon*) to compete against the Australian Broadcasting Corporation's own *World at Noon* – a decision which proved unpopular.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] In 2007, after Tracey Spicer left the network the previous year, Natarsha Belling became the face of the bulletin and continued the role right through to the start of 2012.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] During 2010 and 2011, the bulletin aired for one hour at 9 am, before *The Circle*.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] The bulletin was retired with the launch of *Breakfast* but returned upon the axing of *The Circle* in late August 2012, this time airing at 10 am on weekdays, presented by Ron Wilson.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] Another round of cost-cutting measures led to the morning news being axed again on Friday 23 May 2014, alongside *Wake Up* and the early and late news bulletins.
[src:abc-news-australia/10-news] On 9 December 2025, it was announced that the bulletin would not return in 2026.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] The program was founded by American television producer Gerald Stone, who was appointed its inaugural executive producer in 1979 by media tycoon Kerry Packer.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] Stone devised it to be an Australian version of CBS's American *60 Minutes* program and, upon its inauguration, it featured well-known reporters George Negus, Ray Martin and Ian Leslie.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] Its prominent early programs included a 1981 interview Negus conducted with UK Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, during which the prime minister aggressively countered his questions.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] Negus asked Thatcher why people described her as "pig-headed" and the Prime Minister demanded he tell her who, when and where such comments were made.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] In 1982, Jana Wendt interviewed Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi and asked him why he had been so often described as a terrorist, a butcher, a gangster and a madman.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] In 2019, the program produced a report on the infiltration of organised crime into listed Australian casino firm Crown Resorts.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] It led to multiple state and federal inquiries, including the NSW Bergin Inquiry, that recommended Crown Resorts may be unfit to hold a casino licence.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] In March 2021, the Nine Network launched a one-hour, one-story, studio-based *60 Minutes* spin-off *Under Investigation* presented by Liz Hayes and produced by Gareth Harvey that features a panel of guests.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] In 2018, *60 Minutes* was inducted into the *TV Week* Logie Hall of Fame.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] In 2019, its report on the organised crime infiltration of gaming giant *Crown Resorts* was awarded a Walkley Award and led to two Royal Commissions.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] In 2020, its program on political malfeasance, *The Faceless Man*, was awarded a Walkley Award for best long format television reporting.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] In 2025, the program was nominated for two Logie awards owing to their work on the episode "Building Bad" (Best News Coverage or Current Affairs Report) and one general nomination for Best Current Affairs Program.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] Tara Brown was also nominated to receive the Ray Martin Award for Most Popular News or Public Affairs Presenter.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] An orchestrated incident where his assistant threw water on George Negus during a second appearance on *Today* garnered even more attention for "Carlos".
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] When the sting was revealed on *60 Minutes*, criticism was directed at the network, and reports soon circulated about staff sackings as a result.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] In July 1989, an episode of 60 Minutes entitled "The County" aired on Channel 9, which focused on the Indigenous population of Redfern, New South Wales from the perspective of local police.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] The episode received condemnation from the Koori community for its negative portrayal of the Aboriginal Australian population of Redfern, the invasion of private property by police and reporters during the filming of the episode, and for the use of ethnic slurs by police throughout the episode.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] The episode was the subject of a complaint to the Australian Broadcasting Tribunal, citing "a breach of the Television Program Standards relating to racial vilification".
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] In April 2016, Tara Brown and eight other people (including three other staff members of Nine, David Ballment, Stephen Rice, and Ben Williamson) were arrested on allegations of child abduction in Beirut.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] According to Lebanese authorities, *60 Minutes* allegedly paid $115,000 directly to the Child Abduction Recovery International Agency, despite claims that the exchange was made by the mother of the children.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] The abduction agency used has also been widely discredited, with fake recovery stories being posted on Facebook and their operators having been arrested all over the world.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] The recovery involved the team waiting in a parked car on the street and then snatching the children from their grandmother and nanny before driving away.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] "A Lebanese judicial source" told *The Guardian* that the group were to be charged with "armed abduction, purveying threats and physical harm" – crimes which carry sentences of twenty years' imprisonment with hard labour.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] The group were released from custody only after Nine paid a substantial money settlement to the father of the children the subject of the abduction attempt.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] This operation sparked wide debate about the ethics of the journalism being conducted.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] In May 2019, a jury ruled that a *60 Minutes* story aired in 2015 about the 2011 Grantham floods defamed four members of the Wagner family, from Toowoomba, Queensland, by implying they were responsible for the 12 deaths that occurred during the disaster.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] In November, a court ordered Channel Nine to pay $2.4 million plus $63,000 in interest to the family.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] Nick Cater, a journalist featured in the program, was ordered to pay an additional $1.2 million in damages.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] Justice Peter Applegarth, who was in charge of the case, stated that while Cater had information contradicting the program's allegations, he did not include them in the story.
[src:abc-news-australia/60-minutes-australian-tv-program] Applegarth also concluded that Channel Nine failed to inform the Wagners of the allegations until after the program had been publicised, and when the family did send a statement to Nine, they did not include it in the program.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] The half hour program follows the evening news, and is the flagship program for the network, with *The Sydney Morning Herald* saying "*7.30* remains arguably [the ABC's] most impactful daily program.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] From 1986 to 2011 it was called ***The 7.30 Report***; in 2011 it was rebranded as *7.30* and *Stateline* was folded into the revamped program.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] Until the end of 1995 the program had separate editions for each state and territory, presented by Alan Carpenter, Mary Delahunty, Quentin Dempster, Trisha Goddard, Sarah Henderson, Jane Singleton, Genevieve Hussey, John Jost, Leigh McClusky, Kelly Nestor, and Andrew Olle.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] Kerry O'Brien took over as the presenter of the national program on 4 December 1995, with Maxine McKew serving as the main relief presenter until 2006.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] O'Brien announced in 2010 that he would be leaving at the end of the year.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] He presented his final edition of the program on 9 December 2010.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] In February 1996, the Friday episode of the show was replaced with *Stateline*, a similar show with a separate edition for each state and territory.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] The program usually comprised several pre-recorded items and live interviews, focusing on issues of national or global significance.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] The program traditionally featured interviews with politicians.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] Paul Lyneham also hosted *The 7.30 Report* for several years.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] Until 2010, satirists John Clarke and Bryan Dawe presented a (usually) weekly mock interview covering a topical issue.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] Dawe played the interviewer, while Clarke played a prominent public figure but, unusually for satire, he deliberately made no attempt to imitate the appearance, voice, or mannerisms of the person he portrayed.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] When portraying Julia Gillard he placed a flower pot behind him to give the impression of him being a woman.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] These interviews were a continuation of the pair's work for *A Current Affair*, beginning in 1989, for which they won a number of awards.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] The ABC announced in December 2010 that the program would return in 2011 in a new form, under the name *7.30*.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] The revamped program was first presented by Leigh Sales from Sydney.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] Chris Uhlmann was *7.30'*s first political editor and Canberra presenter.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] The ABC also announced that Stateline would be folded into the *7.30* program.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] The change saw *7.30* extended to five nights a week, although Friday editions continued to be presented locally and focus on state affairs.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] The program first aired on 7 March 2011.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] In 2012, Uhlmann was appointed as *7.30* political editor, therefore stepping down as host.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] Uhlmann remained as political editor until 2013, when he announced that he would be working on a documentary about the Rudd and Gillard governments for the ABC.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] Sabra Lane replaced him as political editor, until she left to host the ABC morning radio current affairs program, *AM*.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] In 2015, Jo Puccini was appointed executive producer of the program.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] In December 2016, the ABC announced that Andrew Probyn would replace Sabra Lane as political editor.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] In August 2017, Probyn moved to a new role as the ABC's political editor replacing Chris Uhlmann who left the broadcaster for the Nine Network.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] In February 2018, Laura Tingle was appointed as political editor, replacing Probyn.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] In 2014, Sarah Ferguson hosted the show whilst Leigh Sales was on maternity leave.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] She received critical acclaim for her hard-hitting interview style from many Australian media outlets.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] In 2018, Justin Stevens was appointed executive producer.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] In February 2022, Sales announced that she would be stepping down as host, after almost 12 years in the role.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] She finished hosting the program in June, after the federal election, but continued to work for the ABC.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] In April 2022, ABC announced that Sarah Ferguson would return from her role as special correspondent in Washington, D.C. to succeed Sales as the host of *7.30* from July 2022.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] Joel Tozer was announced as the new executive producer of the program in June 2022, taking over from Justin Stevens, who was appointed director of news for the network.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] In May 2025, ABC announced that Laura Tingle would be departing *7.30* after six years to take on a new role as global affairs editor.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] Tingle was replaced by Jacob Greber, former chief digital political correspondent at the ABC.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] David Speers is currently a fill-in presenter.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] On 28 November 2014, Quentin Dempster announced the final episode of the state editions would be the following week (5 December 2014), corresponding with his departure from the public broadcaster.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] The state editions of *7.30* were broadcast on ABC at 7:30 p.m., with eight separate state and territory specific editions.
[src:abc-news-australia/7-30] Each local version of *7.30* was also broadcast nationally on ABC News over the weekend.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] It is partially funded by Australia's Department of Foreign Affairs & Trade, as well as some advertising (unlike the ABC's domestic television services).
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Radio Australia had been operating as part of the ABC since 1939 while the passing of the *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* allowed the corporation to operate an additional international television service.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The channel was originally proposed by directors Mark Armstrong and David Hill, who felt that a television channel would further heighten Australia's presence in the Asia-Pacific region and demonstrate the ABC's technical abilities.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Prime Minister Paul Keating launched Australia Television International on 17 February 1993, televised live to 50 countries in the south-east Asian region, from the ABC's television studios in Gore Hill, Sydney.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The actual broadcast was from the Darwin uplink where Dominic Stone, the service's Program Director and David Hill, managing director of the ABC commissioned the first transmission.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The establishment of the new channel was funded by a special government grant of A$5.4 million.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] It was originally a part of the so-called "Gang of Five", which was a consortium that was set up to compete against Star TV in the region.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] (The others in the group were CNN International, HBO, ESPN International [with its Asian operations] and TVB [with TVB Superchannel]) The consortium's channels were initially transmitted via Palapa satellite, but were later also added to Apstar satellite.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The operation of the new channel was funded by a combination of government subsidies and commercial sponsorship.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The presence of commercials, not previously seen or heard on the ABC, resulted in the creation of an updated edition of the *ABC Editorial and Programme Practices*, stipulating that the "Australia Television service will retain editorial control and independence in all programming".
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Funding cuts made in the 1997–1998 federal budget, and recommendations made in the Mansfield Report, meant that control of Australia Television was handed over to the Seven Network in 1998.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Under Seven's direction the channel continued to receive federal funding, and carry some ABC News.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Despite efforts made by Seven to expand into Asia using the service, it continued to lose money.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] In 2001, the government announced a five-year, A$50-million tender for the service – at the time watched primarily by Australian expatriates for its news programmes, football coverage, and children's programming.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Seven chose not to bid, while Imparja Television's application was unsuccessful.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The ABC won the contract and Australia Television was rebranded as ABC Asia Pacific on 1 January 2002 (31 December 2001 by some sources), with content from the Seven Network, Nine Network, Network Ten, and the ABC's own original content, as well as news bulletins produced by Sky News Australia.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The tender was renewed in 2005; the ABC was re-awarded control of the service until 8 August 2011, over other applicants including Sky News Australia.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Soon afterwards, the network stopped showing content from Sky News Australia, replaced with bulletins produced by the ABC's own news and current affairs division from its Southbank studios in Melbourne.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] ABC Asia Pacific changed its name to Australia Network on 7 August 2006, at the same time introducing a number of new programs, as well as the expansion of its existing news programs and English-language learning programs.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Following a restructure of the ABC in early 2007, Australia Network became a part of the corporation's International, Corporate Strategy and Governance division.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The channel was not available in Australia or New Zealand, owing to rights restrictions, although *ABC News for Australia Network* bulletins were carried overnight on ABC News 24 and Al Jazeera English in Australia and on Face TV in New Zealand.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Several Australia Network programmes are also available online in Australia on the ABC's iview platform.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Australia Network became available in Malaysia on Astro (Channel 514) in December 2008.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] In 2010 the Rudd government invited media organisations to submit tenders to deliver the Australia Network for 10 years.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] In November 2011, the Government closed the tender, "due to significant leaks of confidential information to the media", and asked the Australian Federal Police to investigate.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] In the meantime, the ABC's contract was extended until August 2012 to allow time for a decision to be made on its future.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] On 5 December 2011, the Government announced that the Australia Network would no longer be open to tender and that the ABC would take over its operations permanently.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Concerns were raised about the process, and the Australian National Audit Office noted that the tender process "presented the Australian Government in a poor light and cost the two tenderers... time and money".
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The government was obliged to pay millions in compensation to Sky News.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] 80 jobs, mostly in Melbourne, were lost and the government was forced to compensate the ABC A$10.6 million for breaking its contract, which had been promised A$196.8 million in funding for ten years of operation by the previous Labor government.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Following the closure of Australia Network, Australia Plus, a new multi-platform international service was launched on 29 September 2014 as a replacement.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The channel continued to broadcast entertainment, sports, education and English learning shows from ABC through Asia and Pacific partners.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Big events from Australia, such as Melbourne Cup, Sydney's New Year's Eve Fireworks and the Sydney to Hobart Yacht Race were also featured on the channel.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] In 2015, the New Zealand government established *Pasifika TV*, a service providing Pacific island broadcasters with a 24/7 feed of sport, news and other content.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] In August 2016, three commercial partners, the Government of Victoria, vitamin and supplement company Swisse and Monash University signed contracts with Australia Plus.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Under the *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* the ABC International Division is allowed to operate as a commercial operation, in a way similar to BBC Worldwide.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Australia Plus was rebranded as ABC Australia on 1 July 2018.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] In 2020, the Australian Government established *PacificAus TV*, which offers 1000 hours of free Australian commercial TV each year to Pacific island broadcasters.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] In October 2023, the channel established separate schedules for Asia and the Pacific.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The channel broadcasts a mix of programming, including lifestyle, drama, sports, English-language learning programs, children's programming and news and current affairs.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The service is available via subscription to viewers across East Asia, Central Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia and Pacific Islands, including India, Japan, Vietnam, Afghanistan, the Philippines, Papua New Guinea and Vanuatu.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The news programming of the channel is produced and broadcast from the news studios in Sydney, the headquarters of the ABC News channel and the network news service.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] ABC Australia is partially funded by Australia's Department of Foreign Affairs & Trade, as well as some advertising (unlike the ABC's domestic television services).
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] Along with the rest of the ABC, the channel has suffered from successive funding cuts, particularly under Liberal governments since the 1996 Howard government, with particularly deep cuts in 2014 under the Abbott government and an ongoing indexation freeze as of 2021.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] In 2019, the ABC's budget for all international operations was A$11 million, at the same level as it was in the 1980s.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] This compares with the A$3 billion allocated to China Central Television (CCTV) service, and A$500 million for the BBC's international services.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] ABC Radio Australia was launched in 1939, and continues to broadcast in the Asia-Pacific region although no longer on short-wave transmission, so does not reach all of the remote islands.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] The ABC has increased its Internet presence for international audiences; the iview streaming service is available via an app, and ABC News Online includes Chinese-language and Tok Pisin articles.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-australia-asia-pacific-tv-channel] ABC Pacific is the ABC's new digital home for the best Pacific Islands content from across the ABC website since 2022.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] The **ABC Board** is the body responsible for the operations of the Australian Broadcasting Corporation.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] Kim Williams AM is chair; Hugh Marks the managing director appointed by the board; Laura Tingle is a staff-elected member.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] The chair and other directors are chosen by the Australian Government.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] The ABC Board is a board of directors that is responsible for the operations of the Australian Broadcasting Corporation.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] It is made up of five to seven directors chosen by the Australian government, and a managing director who is appointed by the board itself.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] At various times, ABC staff have been granted rights to elect a nominee for appointment to the board; and as of April 2013 staff elected a nominee-director.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] The Governor-General, on the recommendation of the Federal Government, appoints members, as specified in the *ABC Act*.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] The *ABC Act* specifies that Directors must be experienced in broadcasting, communications or management, or have expertise in financial or technical matters, or have cultural or other interests relevant to the provision of broadcasting services.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] Each director serves a term of five years, with eligibility for reappointment at the end of this term.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] Directors are expected to follow the ABC Board Protocol, which stipulates responsibilities, expectations, rights, and benefits.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] The board maintains an Advisory Council, which advises it on matters concerning the Corporation's programming.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] The Council is made up of twelve members, broadly representative of the Australian community, which serve staggered four-year terms.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] Vacancies are advertised in September–October each year.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] The Advisory Council's current Chairman is Dr Jane Munro, Head of International House at the University of Melbourne.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] The Minister for Communications nominates candidates to the Governor-General for appointment to the ABC Board; based on a shortlist prepared by an independent, government-appointed, nomination panel.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] Appointments to the board made by successive governments have often resulted in criticism of the appointees' political affiliation, background, and relative merit.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] From 2003 the Howard government also made several controversial appointments to the ABC Board, including Albrechtsen, a prominent critic, Ron Brunton, and Keith Windschuttle.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] During their 2007 federal election campaign, Labor announced plans to introduce a new system, similar to that of the BBC, for appointing members to the board.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] Under this new system, now in place, ABC candidates are considered by a panel established "at arm's length" from the Communications Minister.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] If the Minister chose someone not on the panel's shortlist, the Minister would be required to justify their selection to Australian Parliament.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] The Chairman of the ABC is nominated by the Prime Minister and endorsed by the Leader of the Opposition.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] David Hill was close to Neville Wran, while Donald McDonald was considered to be a close friend of John Howard.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] In the past, appointments of commissioners and directors also drew criticism.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] In the 1932, a majority of the commissioners were publicly conservative.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] This continued to 1942, when the Curtin and Chifley administrations appointed a more 'politically balanced' commission.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] Once elected to power, Labor prime minister Whitlam replaced the entire board—appointed by Liberal governments over the previous 23 years—with supporters of the Labor Party.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] His successor, Malcolm Fraser, attempted unsuccessfully to take similar action by replacing the board with politically conservative commissioners in 1976, but was only able to make new appointments by adding two extra director positions onto the board.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] In 1983, Minister John Button referred proposed board appointments to an all-party committee for the first time.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] This practice was discontinued before the end of Paul Keating's government.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] A 2006 restructure of the ABC board, undertaken by the Howard government, abolished the position of staff elected director.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] The elected director was previously nominated and elected by employees of the ABC.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] Nominees for this director office were to have been employed at least 24 hours a week by the ABC and the term of office was two years with eligibility for re-election to a second term.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] An elected director was not eligible for a third term of office.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] Broadcaster Ramona Koval had occupied the position for the previous four years prior to its abolition amid ongoing intense controversy.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] This drew criticism from the Labor Party, Australian Greens, and the Democrats, who saw it as a 'revenge measure' taken against the Corporation.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] In July 2007, Labor announced plans to make the system of appointments to the board independent of the Minister for Communications; and also reinstate the staff election of a nominee director.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] Initial members of the independent panel were Gonski, Smith, Allan Fels and Leneen Forde.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] On 24 September 2018, Justin Milne announced to ABC staff that Managing Director Michelle Guthrie was sacked following discussions with the ABC executive and directors.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] Milne then announced his resignation on 27 September.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-board] Communications Minister Mitch Fifield has directly appointed a majority of the current members of the board, some of whom were rejected by the nomination panel.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] The station began broadcasting as ABC-3 on 18 December 1962, soon before prime minister Robert Menzies officially opened the new station at a special reception at Hotel Canberra.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] The "C" in the call sign stands for Canberra.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] Unusually, the station commenced transmission before a local television studio was able to be constructed, with initial transmission of ABC-3 being a direct relay of ABN-2 in Sydney.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] The station opened at 3pm on 18 December 1962 with a test card and music, followed by *Kindergarten Playtime* at 4:45pm.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] ABC-3's main transmitter was constructed at Black Mountain.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] ABC-3 began broadcasting local programs on 3 June 1963 from a temporary studio in the existing 2CN/2CY building in Civic.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] Mervyn Edie was the first person to read the local news on ABC-3.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] New ABC studios were constructed in Northbourne Avenue in Dickson.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] Local ABC radio services commenced broadcasting from the new facility on 3 August 1964.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] ABC-3 commenced television programs from the new studios on 8 October 1964 when the local news became the first program to be broadcast.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] The new studios were officially opened by Postmaster General Alan Hulme on 22 October 1964.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] ABC chairman James Ralph Darling and senator John Gorton also spoke at the event.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] Local television programs to be broadcast from the ABC-3 studios in the station's early years included *Southern Gardener*, *Canberra Week*, *Studio 11*, *Canberra Camera* along with local news, sport and weather.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] For 22 years, ABC-3's local news was a brief five minute bulletin which went to air each night at 6:55pm.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] This ended on 15 February 1985 as the station prepared to produce a new 10-minute bulletin which was expected to go to air at approximately 7:20pm each night towards the end of the ABC's new national news program *The National* hosted by Richard Morecroft and Geraldine Doogue.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] When Wilson left in late 1989, she was replaced with Claudia Emery.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] Emery continued to present the bulletin until August 1991 when local news production was entirely axed amid the Hawke government's funding cut to the ABC totaling $15 million.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] The local *ABC News* bulletin was replaced with the New South Wales edition presented by Richard Morecroft from Sydney.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] Emery and weather presenter Peter Leonard were among the attendees of a "wake" which had been organised following the airing of the final local *ABC News* bulletin in Canberra.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] A local ACT edition of *ABC News* was re-introduced in 2001, presented by Virginia Haussegger.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] This was the same year that Southern Cross Broadcasting axed *Ten Capital News*, leaving the ABC and WIN Television as being the only stations to have a locally presented news bulletin from studios in Canberra.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] When WIN Television closed their Canberra studio in 2013 and relocated the production of their local *WIN News* bulletin to Wollongong, New South Wales, the ABC was left as the only remaining station to have a locally presented news bulletin produced in Canberra for ACT viewers.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] Canberra was the first city in Australia in which analogue television was switched off, in 2012, meaning that only digital television services are transmitted.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] In November 2014, it was announced the long-running weekly local current affairs program *7.30 ACT* (previously known as *Stateline*) would be axed due to the Abbott government's funding cuts to the ABC.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] The final edition went to air on 5 December 2014.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] After 15 year of reading *ABC News Canberra*, Virginia Haussegger resigned and read her final bulletin in October 2016.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] Haussegger was succeeded by Dan Bourchier who started presenting *ABC News Canberra* in January 2017.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] In 2019, the ABC in Canberra introduced an Acknowledgement of Country during *ABC News Canberra*.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] As part of our ongoing commitment to Indigenous recognition, the ABC is partnering with the United Ngunnawal Elders Council and pays respect to them — the first people of this land.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] Bourchier had opened the bulletin by saying "Yuma", the traditional greeting with graphics behind him including the words "Ngunnawal Country".
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] A new standing set was installed in July 2022, to allow *ABC News* presenters to either stand at the news desk or in front of the large plasma screen with relevant graphics displayed behind them.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] At the end of 2022, former ABC foreign correspondent James Glenday was announced as the new host of *ABC News Canberra*.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] It was announced in May 2023 that ABC TV's Sunday morning public affairs program *Insiders* hosted by David Speers would be relocating to the Canberra studio after more than two decades of being broadcast live from the Melbourne studio.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] The first edition of *Insiders* to be broadcast live from Canberra went to air on 9 July 2023.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] As of 2021 there are four transmitters broadcasting ABC channels 8, 36 and 41, with one still situated on Black Mountain.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] Most households in New South Wales near the border to ACT such as Queanbeyan, Cooma, Goulburn and Yass receive the Canberra edition of the ABC 7pm bulletin.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] The weeknight bulletins incorporate a national finance section presented by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] A new studio set was introduced in mid-2014 to match the rest of the ABC News network.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] There was another studio upgrade in 2022, making the studio completely standing.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-canberra-tv-station] The weekly current affairs program, *7.30 ACT* was presented by Chris Kimball until its cancellation in 2014 in a round of severe cuts to the ABC.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:abc-news-australia/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
